In a speech delivered at the National Law Enforcement Officers Memorial Service, President Biden addressed the recent mass shooting in Buffalo, New York, expressing condolences to the victims' families and emphasizing the need to address hate and violence in America. He recognized the difficult and complex role of law enforcement officers in today's world, acknowledging the challenges they face in dealing with issues such as drug addiction, domestic violence, and mental health crises. President Biden highlighted the importance of funding the police and investing in community policing, crime prevention, and violence intervention programs. He also emphasized the need to improve mental health support for both officers and the community. The President called for the reauthorization of the Violence Against Women Act and urged Congress to reach an agreement on meaningful policing legislation to strengthen public trust and safety. President Biden concluded his speech by acknowledging the pain and courage of the families present and expressing hope that the nation can find a purpose worthy of the lives lost.